{
  "text": "Zebrafish (Danio rerio) has become a widely used model organism, due to its fast development, high progeny number, transparency and ease of use. These advantages made it the subject of multiple extremely successful genetic screens, which have identified many key genes in diverse developmental processes, DV patterning being one of these [CITATION_1] . From these screens, mutations that lead to DV patterning defects have often turned out to occur in genes that encode elements of the BMP signaling pathway (see [CITATION_2] and references therein). However, some other key factors of early DV patterning have also been identified both by these screens and by other reverse genetic approaches [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The picture that emerges from these studies suggests that early zebrafish DV patterning is following a similar logic to that observed in the African clawed frog, Xenopus laevis [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "15678579",
